# вЪ†пЄП 2. `any` (THE MOST DANGEROUS TYPE)

```ts
let value: any = 10;
value = "hello";
value = true;
```

рЯСЙ TypeScript basically says:

> вАЬDo whatever you want, I wonвАЩt check.вАЭ

### вЭМ Problem:

```ts
value.toUpperCase(); // рЯТ• runtime crash if value is number
```

---

## рЯФ• Interview Insight:

> вАЬ`any` disables TypeScript completely. It should be avoided unless absolutely necessary.вАЭ

---

# рЯІ† 3. `unknown` (SMART VERSION OF `any`)

```ts
let value: unknown = "hello";
```

рЯСЙ You CANNOT directly use it:

```ts
value.toUpperCase(); // вЭМ Error
```

### вЬЕ You must check first:

```ts
if (typeof value === "string") {
  console.log(value.toUpperCase());
}
```

---

## рЯФ• Key Difference

| Feature             | any вЭМ | unknown вЬЕ |
| ------------------- | ----- | --------- |
| Safety              | No    | Yes       |
| Type check required | No    | Yes       |

рЯСЙ Golden rule:

> Use `unknown` instead of `any`

---

# рЯІ† 4. `void` (FUNCTION RETURNS NOTHING)

```ts
function logMessage(msg: string): void {
  console.log(msg);
}
```

рЯСЙ Means:

> вАЬThis function doesnвАЩt return anythingвАЭ

---

# рЯІ† 5. `null` and `undefined`

```ts
let a: null = null;
let b: undefined = undefined;
```

рЯСЙ In strict mode:
You must explicitly allow them.

```ts
let name: string | null = null;
```

---

# рЯТА 6. `never` (VERY IMPORTANT рЯФ•)

рЯСЙ Represents:

> вАЬThis will NEVER happenвАЭ

### Example 1: Infinite loop

```ts
function infiniteLoop(): never {
  while (true) {}
}
```

### Example 2: Error throwing

```ts
function throwError(msg: string): never {
  throw new Error(msg);
}
```

---

## рЯФ• Interview Insight:

Difference between `void` vs `never`

| Type  | Meaning              |
| ----- | -------------------- |
| void  | returns nothing      |
| never | never returns at all |

---

# рЯІ† 7. Type Inference (SUPER IMPORTANT)

рЯСЙ TypeScript is smart:

```ts
let x = 10; // TS automatically: number
```

You donвАЩt always need to write types.

---

## вЪ†пЄП BUT:

```ts
